skill.name: seaborn
skill.description: Statistical visualization with pandas integration. Use for quick exploration of distributions, relationships, and categorical comparisons with attractive defaults. Best for box plots, violin plots, pair plots, heatmaps. Built on matplotlib. For interactive plots use plotly; for publication styling use scientific-visualization.

security_audit.summary: This is a documentation-only skill for seaborn statistical visualization library. The static scanner falsely flagged markdown code blocks as shell commands. All 'external_commands' findings are actually python code examples in markdown syntax. No executable code, network calls, or file operations present.

content.value_statement: Transform raw data into insightful statistical visualizations without complex matplotlib code. Seaborn provides beautiful, publication-ready plots with automatic statistical estimation and pandas integration.
actual_capabilities: Generate publication-quality statistical plots with minimal code
Create distribution plots, correlation matrices, and regression visualizations
Apply statistical transformations and confidence intervals
limitations: Requires matplotlib for customization beyond defaults

best_practices: Use figure-level functions (relplot, catplot, displot) for automatic faceting instead of manual subplots
Structure data in long-form with meaningful column names for automatic axis labels and legends
Set appropriate context ('paper', 'talk', 'poster') before creating figures for consistent sizing
anti_patterns: Creating individual subplots manually when figure-level functions could handle faceting automatically
Using arrays instead of DataFrames, which loses automatic labeling and semantic mapping capabilities
Forgetting to set random seed when using statistical functions that involve bootstrapping or sampling

faq.question: What's the difference between axes-level and figure-level functions?
faq.answer: Axes-level functions plot to a single subplot (scatterplot, histplot), while figure-level functions manage entire figures with built-in faceting (relplot, displot, catplot).

faq.question: How do I save high-resolution figures?
faq.answer: Use .savefig() on the returned object with dpi=300 for print quality: g.savefig('figure.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')

faq.question: Can I combine seaborn with matplotlib?
faq.answer: Yes, seaborn returns matplotlib objects. Store the result: ax = sns.scatterplot(...) then customize with ax.set_title(), ax.axhline(), etc.

faq.question: Why are my categorical plots overlapping?
faq.answer: Use dodge=True to separate hue levels side-by-side, or adjust figure size with height/aspect parameters for figure-level functions.

faq.question: How do I handle large datasets?
faq.answer: Sample your data before plotting, use stat='density' instead of 'count' for histograms, or reduce plot complexity with fewer facets.

faq.question: What's the best plot type for my data?
faq.answer: Continuous vs continuous: scatterplot or lineplot. Continuous vs categorical: boxplot or violinplot. Single continuous: histplot or kdeplot.
